 0368: 
 0369: 
 0370: ###################################
 0371: # Event handling
 0372: ###################################
 0373: 
 0374: # We need custom event handling in a few ways:
 0375: #   -- We need to listen to various events on client windows, even though they
 0376: #      have no GtkWidget associated.
 0377: #   -- We need to listen to various events that are not otherwise wrapped by
 0378: #      GDK at all.  (In particular, the SubstructureRedirect events.)
 0379: # To do this, we use two different hooks in GDK:
 0380: #   gdk_window_add_filter: This allows us to snoop on all events before they
 0381: #     are converted into GDK events.  We use this to capture:
 0382: #       MapRequest
 0383: #       ConfigureRequest
 0384: #       FocusIn
 0385: #       FocusOut
 0386: #       ClientMessage
 0387: #     (We could get ClientMessage from PyGTK using the API below, but
 0388: #     PyGTK's ClientMessage handling is annoying -- see bug #466990.)
 0389: #   gdk_event_handler_set: This allows us to snoop on all events after they
 0390: #     have gone through the GDK event handling machinery, just before they
 0391: #     enter GTK.  Everything that we catch in this manner could just as well
 0392: #     be caught by the gdk_window_add_filter technique, but waiting until here
 0393: #     lets us write less binding gunk.  We use this to catch:
 0394: #       PropertyNotify
 0395: #       Unmap
 0396: #       Destroy
 0397: # Our hooks in any case use the "xpra-route-events-to" GObject user data
 0398: # field of the gdk.Window's involved.  For the SubstructureRedirect
 0399: # events, we use this field of either the window that is making the request,
 0400: # or, if its field is unset, to the window that actually has
 0401: # SubstructureRedirect selected on it; for other events, we send it to the
 0402: # event window directly.
 0403: #
 0404: # So basically, to use this code:
 0405: #   -- Import this module to install the global event filters
 0406: #   -- Call win.set_data("xpra-route-events-to", obj) on random windows.
 0407: #   -- Call addXSelectInput or its convenience wrappers, substructureRedirect
 0408: #      and selectFocusChange.
 0409: #   -- Receive interesting signals on 'obj'.
 0410: 
 0411: cdef extern from "gtk-3.0/gdk/gdkevents.h":
 0412:     ctypedef enum GdkFilterReturn:
 0413:         GDK_FILTER_CONTINUE   # If we ignore the event
 0414:         GDK_FILTER_TRANSLATE  # If we converted the event to a GdkEvent
 0415:         GDK_FILTER_REMOVE     # If we handled the event and GDK should ignore it
 0416: 
 0417:     ctypedef struct GdkXEvent:
 0418:         pass
 0419:     ctypedef struct GdkEvent:
 0420:         pass
 0421: 
 0422:     ctypedef GdkFilterReturn (*GdkFilterFunc)(GdkXEvent *, GdkEvent *, void *)
 0423:     void gdk_window_add_filter(GdkWindow * w,
 0424:                                GdkFilterFunc filter,
 0425:                                void * userdata)
 0426: 
 0427:     void gdk_window_remove_filter(GdkWindow *window,
 0428:                                GdkFilterFunc function,
 0429:                                void * data)
 0430: 
 0431: 
 0432: # No need to select for ClientMessage; in fact, one cannot select for
 0433: # ClientMessages.  If they are sent with an empty mask, then they go to the
 0434: # client that owns the window they are sent to, otherwise they go to any
 0435: # clients that are selecting for that mask they are sent with.
+0436: WINDOW_EVENT_RECEIVERS_KEY = "_xpra_window_event_receivers"
  if (PyDict_SetItem(__pyx_d, __pyx_n_s_WINDOW_EVENT_RECEIVERS_KEY, __pyx_n_u_xpra_window_event_receivers) < 0) __PYX_ERR(0, 436, __pyx_L1_error)
